<h1>Two in a row</h1>
<p id="issuedate"><strong>Issued: Tue, 01 Sep 2009 14:38:00 BST</strong></p>
<p>Mr Iain Houston, an alumnus of the University and holder of the Postgraduate Certificate of Education from the Faculty of Education in 2004-05, beat very stiff competition to be awarded the accolade of Scottish Teacher of the Year at the 2009 Scottish Education Awards.&nbsp; He is the second Glasgow University Faculty of Education student to have been in receipt of the award in as many years, following last year’s winner, David Miller who also claimed the UK Teacher of the Year Award.</p>
<p>Ian who is a physics teacher at St Joseph's College in Dumfries impressed the judges with his original approach to teaching, which included the use of Dr Who and science from 19th century experiments.</p>
<p>Ian said, “I would like to give the University my thanks for stimulating my own intellectual and pedagogical development. I thoroughly enjoyed my year in the Faculty of Education and am particularly grateful for the support and guidance of my physics and maths lecturers, Elizabeth Aitkenhead and Willie Magill.&nbsp; I would be delighted to return to the Faculty and give something back in the form of workshops to the PGDE students.”</p>
<p>We are delighted with Ian’s success and wish him every success in the forthcoming awards in London for UK Teacher of the Year where he will be flying the flag for Scotland.</p>
<p>Professor James C Conroy<br />Dean </p>
